Agreed; it's called canning, regardless of the container. My mother had a huge pressure canner. It contained jars. Google "pressure canner" for evidence. When food writers refer to "jarred tomato sauce" it looks so precious to me (even though I know that the stuff in actual cans is inferior.)

My dad used to tell the joke about the Britisher visiting an American farm. He asked the farmer "how do you use all the food you grow?" The reply was "We eat what we can, and what we can't we can." Returning home the Brit tried to amuse his friends with the story. But in doing so he said "we eat what we can, and what we can't we preserve."

